<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-28T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-28T18:00:00-05:00" n="106" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d106">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3689: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="from">Cunningham</persName>) to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-29T07:00:00+08:00">January 29, 1932—7
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 28—11:28 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Japanese Navy with slight resistance occupied Chapei about midnight while
                            all were lulled into a [sense?] of relief by the assurance of <pb facs="0194" n="90" xml:id="pg_90"/> Japanese to full [<hi rend="italic">consular?</hi>] body at 4 o’clock yesterday afternoon.
                            The troop movements are stated to be on the ground of protection of
                            large number Japanese in Chapei. Occasional heavy artillery is heard in
                            that direction as well as planes plainly visible. Details will
                            follow.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Department [<hi rend="italic">Legation?</hi>].</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_CES1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>